{"source_key":"sha256-fa9f53017eb5571f2178aa90c1e14f29","record_index":80,"record_hash":"sha256:ca0426d96f47e054c10a954d3d23ee9e304d46022e89d51a532e4eb1d460bb2d","timestamp":"2026-05-20T14:52:02.244Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 594811\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 954\nOutput:\n   612\tThese still are not durable ownership claims. They mean \"this target was visible\n   613\tin the repository state around this capture turn.\"\n   614\t\n   615\t### Automatic Scoring\n   616\t\n   617\tThe preferred product direction is no required human confirmation. Capture\n   618\tstores observations and lookup indexes. Read paths compute an association score\n   619\tand show related sessions automatically when confidence is high enough.\n   620\t\n   621\tDo not persist automatic scoring results as durable relationships in v1. They\n   622\tshould be derived read-time results with a scoring version, confidence label,\n   623\tscore, and highlighted turn keys. A future cache is fine if it is explicitly\n   624\trebuildable derived data.\n   625\t\n   626\tSuggested result shape:\n   627\t\n   628\t```json\n   629\t{\n   630\t  \"session_key\": \"sha256-...\",\n   631\t  \"turn_keys\": [\"sha256-...\"],\n   632\t  \"score\": 82,\n   633\t  \"confidence\": \"high\",\n   634\t  \"scoring_version\": \"agentlog-association.v1\"\n   635\t}\n   636\t```\n   637\t\n   638\tThe exact numeric scale can change, but the first heuristic should be simple and\n   639\texplainable:\n   640\t\n   641\t- explicit user/API relationships, if they exist, win\n   642\t- previous worktree files later appearing in observed commits is strong evidence\n   643\t- observed review id, pull request, or change id is strong candidate evidence\n   644\t- observed branch name is useful candidate evidence but weak on its own\n   645\t- repeated observation across many turns strengthens a session-level result\n   646\t- broad or truncated file lists weaken file-overlap evidence\n   647\t- multiple visible branches/stacks weaken branch-name evidence\n   648\t- missing or failed environment snapshots simply produce less evidence\n   649\t\n   650\tUse confidence buckets for product behavior, with numeric scores only as an\n   651\tinternal sorting aid:\n   652\t\n   653\t- `high`: show automatically as likely related\n   654\t- `medium`: show as possibly related or secondary context\n   655\t- `low`: hide by default, but keep available for debugging or expanded context\n   656\t- `none`: no meaningful signal\n   657\t\n   658\tInitial v1 bucket rules should stay conservative:\n   659\t\n   660\t- direct change-id observation is high confidence\n   661\t- previous-turn worktree files later appearing in commit files on the queried\n   662\t  target is high confidence\n   663\t- direct review or pull request observation is high confidence only when\n   664\t  supported by repeated session activity or file/commit evidence\n   665\t- a single branch-name observation is medium at best, and low in a multi-branch\n   666\t  workspace without other evidence\n   667\t- repeated branch observation can move a result toward medium, but should not\n   668\t  become high without stronger evidence\n   669\t- broad/truncated file lists, many visible branches, or failed snapshots should\n   670\t  downrank confidence\n   671\t- backfill turns should downrank environment-based evidence because their\n   672\t  snapshot was taken after the historical transcript records already existed\n   673\t- common noisy paths such as lockfiles, generated files, shared config, and very\n   674\t  broad renames should be downranked as overlap evidence\n   675\t\n   676\tThe exact weights and thresholds should be tuned during implementation with real\n   677\tcaptured sessions. Even high-confidence results should be phrased as related\n   678\tsession evidence, not proof that the agent produced the code.\n   679\t\n   680\tBecause v1 does not write a path index, file-overlap evidence only boosts\n   681\tcandidates discovered through branch, review, or change indexes. A session that\n   682\tonly shares file paths with a target, but never observed that target, can be\n   683\tmissed in v1. That is an acceptable tradeoff for keeping the first index lean.\n   684\t\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T14:52:02.244Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}